pr_review_comment_body:
WOW! Super! This is how far we go for open source! 🎉

Let me share my benchmarks with you:

Name (time in ns)    |        Min          |        Max          |       Mean          | StdDev          |     Median          |    IQR          | Outliers  OPS (Kops/s)          | Rounds | Iterations
---------------------|---------------------|---------------------|---------------------|-----------------|---------------------|-----------------|---------------------------------|--------|-----------
test_with_endswith   |   422.3146 (1.00)   |   441.1720 (1.02)   |   428.6322 (1.01)   | 7.4089 (4.96)   |   426.0483 (1.00)   | 7.9161 (4.70)   |      1;0    2,333.0027 (0.99)   |      5 |   10000000
test_with_rstrip     |   528.8423 (1.25)   |   532.5924 (1.24)   |   531.3621 (1.25)   | 1.4928 (1.0)    |   531.7795 (1.25)   | 1.6846 (1.0)    |      1;0    1,881.9557 (0.80)   |      5 |    1895592
test_with_match      | 1,164.0312 (2.76)   | 1,171.8660 (2.72)   | 1,167.8383 (2.74)   | 3.7479 (2.51)   | 1,166.3237 (2.75)   | 6.9720 (4.14)   |      3;0      856.2829 (0.36)   |      5 |    1000000

Generated from:

```python
import pytest
import re


class TestEndswithRstripMatch(object):

    text = 'cat: /foo/bar/: Is a directory\n'

    def with_match(self):
        return re.match(r'cat: .+: Is a directory', self.text)

    @pytest.mark.benchmark(group='endswith vs rstrip vs match')
    def test_with_match(self, benchmark):
        result = benchmark(self.with_match)
        assert result

    def with_rstrip(self):
        return self.text.startswith('cat: ') and self.text.rstrip().endswith(': Is a directory')

    @pytest.mark.benchmark(group='endswith vs rstrip vs match')
    def test_with_rstrip(self, benchmark):
        result = benchmark(self.with_rstrip)
        assert result

    def with_endswith(self):
        return self.text.startswith('cat: ') and self.text.endswith(': Is a directory\n')

    @pytest.mark.benchmark(group='endswith vs rstrip vs match')
    def test_with_endswith(self, benchmark):
        result = benchmark(self.with_endswith)
        assert result
```

You might as well need `$ pip install pytest-benchmark` and [these docs](http://pytest-benchmark.readthedocs.io/en/latest/usage.html#commandline-options).

So, sure. Let's go for the `rstrip`less version and make it more tolerant in the future, if necessary.

```python
from scrapyd.runner import main scrapyd_main

def start_coverage():
    cov =...
    cov.start()
    coverage.process_startup()

def main():
    start_coverage()
    try:
        return main()
    finally:
        save_coverage()
```

But I've just realised that it should actually be 

if (blob1[2] == -1) or (blob2[2] == -1)):

Because the 'radius' is at index 2. Apologies.

Same here

    if 'apiToken' not in access_credential:

should be

    if 'apiToken' not in self.access_credential:

@jgeewax Who should we reach out to about this question? HBase/Thrift allow the columns to created when the table is, but [`CreateTableRequest`][1] does not.

To deal with it here we could also try to clean up, e.g. if there is any failure during creation, we try to delete all the things that were created. But IMO that is opening Pandora's box.

[1]: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/cloud-bigtable-client/blob/7c77c170c8818a0440e0d2f4ecedcb8329c1f8d9/bigtable-protos/src/main/proto/google/bigtable/admin/table/v1/bigtable_table_service_messages.proto#L26

This is not how documentation is formatted now. It should be something like:
```
    'documentation': {
        'description': 'An attribute of type bool with read/write access.',
    },
```

you can also lift the inner merge(s) into `mergeWith`, but maybe overly concise:
```js
return R.mergeWith(R.merge, state, {images: action.payload.entities.images})

`app`? I didn't really know what to call this, it's really the top-most part of the `core` state. The alternative would be to assume that *all* of this is wrapped in `core` and so we don't need an `app` wrapper:

```
state = {
  core: {
    selectedContentRef: Ref,
    ...
    preferences: { .. },
    communication: { .. },
    ...
  }
}
```

nit: You can use
```javascript
_.forOwn(descriptions, function(value, description) {
  ...
});
```

`sliders` should always be a NodeList, so will always be truthy:
```js
var x = document.querySelectorAll('.not-very-likely'); [!!x, x.length]
// [true, 0]
```
You can dissolve this `if`-statement, and just use:
```js
this.querySelectorAll('paper-slider').forEach(slider => {
  slider[value] = runToStepIndex[slider.dataset.run];
});
```
